If you're one of us, you have to use the CustomBinding to query the database, reporting the criteria for sort, group and filter the income data, and then convert back the result to the ViewModels.

Sounds simple, but can become a very complicated and repetitive task.

So I, with the help of some comrades of development, have created a way to automate this in a very generic way.

This code is highly experimental and has no guarantee that works perfectly in all cases.

Selenium is a set of different software tools each with a different approach to supporting browser automation. These tools are highly flexible, allowing many options for locating and manipulating elements within a browser, and one of its key features is the support for automating multiple browser platforms. This package contains the .NET bindings for the older, more procedural Selenium Remote Control (or Selenium RC) API. It requires a running instance of the Selenium Server, and uses JavaScript for automating the browser, which means it is limited to the functionality available from within the JavaScript sandbox.
summary: .NET bindings for the Selenium RC API

DotNetCompression is a streaming compression library that provides six lossless data compression methods with a variety of characteristics: LZF3, DEFLATE, ZLIB, GZIP, BZIP2 and LZMA. From fast compression to high compression, DotNetCompression offers you a comprehensive set of compression methods to choose from that cover a wide range of needs and are easy to switch even in runtime. DotNetCompression includes managed assemblies for .NET Framework, .NET Compact Framework, Silverlight, Azure, Windows Phone 7, Xbox 360, Mono, MonoTouch and Mono for Android.
summary: DotNetCompression provides 100% managed LZF3, DEFLATE, ZLIB, GZIP, BZIP2 and LZMA compression streams.

This package contains the .NET bindings for the older, more procedural Selenium Remote Control (or Selenium RC) API, but implemented using the newer WebDriver technology. It is intended as a transitional package to allow organizations with significant investment in the Selenium RC API to run their code with minimal modifications until they are able to migrate to the newer Selenium WebDriver API.
